Here comes a little series of photos from our nerdy trip:

We decided to go by tramway and Metro. The tramway is needed to get to La Defense from Suresnes. In fact we would even have to pay for another zone but (un)fortunately the ticket machine at the station was broken…
after having been waiting for quite a while for the tramway in Suresnes.
Robert and Kasper in metro line 1 from La Defense going downtown.

In fact we should have switched to line 6 or something like that at “Charles de Gaulle – Etoile” but we completely forgot to get out of the train and before we knew better we were at “Champs-Elysees Clemenceau” station.
So we decided to punish ourselves for this stupidity and walk the distance to the
by foot. I also knew the “Champs-Elysees” metro station anyways since I had been watching Tour de France there some weeks before with Rie, my Nikon D100 and Sigma Telezoom:

I know thousands of people are going to read this so I better write something intelligent… I know thousands of people are going to read this so I better write something intelligent… I know thousands of people are going to read this so I better write something intelligent… I know thousands of people are going to read this so I better write something intelligent…
Le Guru at some bridge over The Seine
Well, finally after having been walking for some 20 minutes in the hot and humid

evening we finally entered the iron tower. Yes, of course we would take the elevator, who wouldn’t when you considered how warm it was in the air… But the line was longer than the TSref and you could probably install TYPO3 five times on a RedHat 6 before you would get to the top.
So we walked, well knowing this would be an athletic exercise and also the last day we could justify to wear our shirts…
Mr. Robert on the stairs to the first floor. If you have ever seen how long the line for the elevators are even at 22:00 you can understand why we went only to the first floor by foot!

Tour Eiffel really is an amazing construction, my favourite in fact. And in particular when it is lit by thousands of lamps giving it an impressing glow in the night. The perfect surrounding for starting a new extension which would probably hit the heart of many people. And generate income “pour poor” Robert Lemke.
Kasper thinking reeeally hard about something.

We approached the work by creating a framework on Kaspers laptop and luckily he brought it along since Roberts high-tech “I have 6 hours battery” laptop wasn’t much help when it turned out that the large battery was… empty. But anyways, we got the extension nicely started, sitting there 50 meters over the ground with a magnificient view over Napoleons city. So great.
Finally we celebrated the efforts with a “totally crazy” (Vincents favourite English expression) taxi drive home to the other brink of The Seine. But that story you can hear another time.
